      male:   'Blazon is a precise language — every word carries a specific visual instruction, and ambiguity in the description produces ambiguity in the arms, which produces disputes, which is the problem the language exists to prevent. He spent six months learning to describe any coat of arms in correct blazon without reference and then another six months learning to see the error in an incorrect blazon immediately. He can now look at an armorial and hear the description simultaneously. It is a useful doubling of perception.',
      female: 'The arms of the thirty-seven noble families currently in feud with each other, their cadency marks, their augmentations, and the disputed elements in twelve ongoing heraldic cases — she has memorised all of it. The master said memorisation was not the point; understanding the underlying grammar was the point. She said the memorisation was how she got to the grammar. They agreed this was an acceptable process after she demonstrated it.',
